										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p>Nigeria is now Airtel Africa’s second-biggest market by revenue earned from each subscriber, as higher telecom tariffs boosted earnings in the company’s largest African market.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Airtel Africa, which operates in<a href="https://www.airtel.africa/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"> 14 countries</a>, grew its average revenue per user (ARPU) in Nigeria by 41.18% for the financial year ended March 2026, according to the <a href="https://cdn-webportal.airtelstream.net/website/investor/main/pdf/Q4-2026/Press_release_FY'2026.pdf" type="link" id="https://cdn-webportal.airtelstream.net/website/investor/main/pdf/Q4-2026/Press_release_FY'2026.pdf">company’s financial results</a> released on Friday. </p>



<p>ARPU measures how much telecom operators earn per subscriber and is a key indicator of whether revenue is sufficient to cover operating costs and fund network investments.&nbsp;</p>



